     blogpost, consider whether this approach, or parts of it, could help you.

20 | 2.3 Preparing to search
2.4 Unpacking the research question

You will commence the search process by unpacking your research question to identify the discreet
research concepts in your question. Next, you will look for the associated keywords for each of those
research concepts. Some of these keywords may be the same or similar to the words identified for your
research concepts in your question. After that, consider any synonyms and related terms for each of
those keywords. Finally, you can include any subject headings or controlled vocabulary that could be
used to search for those research concepts. You may even find some of these subject headings or con-
trolled vocabulary terms are the same words you identified as your research concepts or may be more
appropriate research concepts for your research question. All these search terms will be used to con-
struct your searches. We will look at these steps in more depth below.

                    An interactive H5P element has been excluded from this version of the text. You can view it online here:
                    https://qut.pressbooks.pub/airs/?p=718#h5p-96

1. Identify research concepts

Your research concepts are the most important words in your research question. These concepts will
form the basis of the keywords, synonyms and related terms you use to start constructing your search.
One of the best ways to quickly understand what you are researching is to identify the concepts in your
research question. These concepts describe the kinds of information you need to investigate to answer
your question. You will do this by analysing your question to identify the exact things you want to know
more about and then documenting those concepts in a list, table, or visual map, and showing how
they relate to one another in order to guide your searching.
Maintain flexibility, as your research question may evolve with growing knowledge in your field, emerg-
ing terminology, and advances in related research.
In this example question, the research concepts have been identified to help construct a search to find
related literature.

                                                                                                                                  2.4 Unpacking the research question | 21
 "Does the experience of moving interstate to commence first-year university have an influence on
                                established study routines for school-leaving teenagers?"

     Watch

     See the video below for a research supervisor's perspective about preparing to find information by identi-
     fying research concepts and associated keywords.

                          One or more interactive elements has been excluded from this version of the text. You can view
                          them online here: https://qut.pressbooks.pub/airs/?p=718#oembed-2

                                                              Preparing to find information (QUT YouTube video, 0m58s).

2. Finding keywords, synonyms and related terms

After identifying your research concepts, you will explore keywords, relevant synonyms, and related
terms. Naturally, some of these will be the same or similar to the words in your research concepts. This
helps refine your search strategy within the theoretical framework of your topic and ensures you cap-
ture all pertinent research, even when different terminology is used.
To begin this process:

  · list keywords for each research concept
  · list synonyms that come to mind for each keyword
  · list any related terms for each keyword
  · include singular and plural forms of the words
  · include alternate spelling variations.
You might like to use a dictionary to explore the meaning of terms or look for synonyms in a thesaurus.
Generative Artificial Intelligence (GenAI) can be a useful tool to help you brainstorm synonyms and
related terms for keywords in your research question. Whether you use AI functionality within a data-
base or a stand-alone tool designed to support this type of activity, you should use the generated terms
as words as a starting point for your own exploration of the topic.
Next, consider more broad associations with other words and concepts that have a highly relevant and
contextual relationship to your research question. For example, when looking for information about the
common cold, it could help to include the term virus because a type of virus causes the common cold.
Similarly, if you are researching heart attacks, you might wish to include the related term emergency

22 | 2.4 Unpacking the research question
room as many people who experience a heart attack will attend hospital. These additional words will
become your related search terms.

     Watch

     See the video below for advice about how to unpack the research question to identify research concepts,
     keywords and related search terms using GenAI tools.

                          One or more interactive elements has been excluded from this version of the text. You can view
                          them online here: https://qut.pressbooks.pub/airs/?p=718#oembed-3

